{{Infobox Bishopric |border = catholic |font_color = black |bishopric = [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] |coatofarms = |image = |incumbent = [[Alan Williams SM|Alan Williams]]<ref>Nevertheless, he still must take canonical possession of the diocese according to [http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/_P1E.HTM canon 382] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208184156/http://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/_P1E.HTM |date=December 8, 2013 }}.</ref> |province = [[Province of Westminster|Westminster]] |diocese = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brentwood|Brentwood]] |cathedral = [[Brentwood Cathedral|St Mary's and St Helen's, Brentwood]] |first_bishop = [[Bernard Nicholas Ward]] |date = 20 July 1917 |website = }}
The '''Bishop of Brentwood''' is the [[Ordinary (officer)|Ordinary]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brentwood]] in the [[Province of Westminster]], England.<ref name=dbren>{{Catholic-hierarchy|diocese|dbren|Diocese of Brentwood|26 June 2011}}</ref>
==Overview== The diocese covers the historic county of Essex, an area of {{convert|3959|km2|sqmi|-2|abbr=on}} comprising the non-metropolitan county of [[Essex]], the unitary authorities of [[Southend-on-Sea]] and [[Thurrock]], and from [[Greater London]], the London Boroughs of [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham|Barking & Dagenham]], [[London Borough of Havering|Havering]], [[London Borough of Newham|Newham]], [[London Borough of Redbridge|Redbridge]] and [[London Borough of Waltham Forest|Waltham Forest]], matching Essex's [[Historic counties of England|historic boundaries]] and the [[Anglican]] [[Diocese of Chelmsford]]. The [[Episcopal see|see]] is in the town of [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] where the [[Cathedra|bishop's seat]] is located at the [[Brentwood Cathedral|Cathedral]] Church of [[Saint Mary]] and [[Helena (Empress)|Saint Helen]].
==History== The diocese was erected on 20 July 1917 from the [[Archdiocese of Westminster]]. The current bishop is the Right Reverend '''[[Thomas McMahon (bishop)|Thomas McMahon]]''', the 6th Bishop of Brentwood, who announced his retirement in 2011. On 14 April 2014, it was announced that Fr Alan Williams SM, a priest with the [[Society of Mary (Marists)|Society of Mary]] and director of the [[Slipper Chapel|Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham]], would become the next Bishop of Brentwood.<ref>[http://www.indcatholicnews.com/news.php?viewStory=24551 Pope appoints new Bishop of Brentwood] from ''Independent Catholic News'' retrieved 14 April 2014</ref>
