{{Islam by country}}
'''Islam in French Polynesia''' is a small religious minority in the territory of [[French Polynesia]]. There are an estimated 500 Muslims in French Polynesia,<ref>[http://www.refworld.org/docid/53ba8dbb5.html State of the World's Minorities and Indigenous Peoples 2014 - Case study: Tahiti: Islamophobia in French Polynesia]</ref> most of which are in Tahiti, where the only mosque exists in [[Papeete]]. The mosque opened in 2013 and its imam is Hicham el-Berkani,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/224849/first-mosque-opens-in-french-polynesia | title=First mosque opens in French Polynesia | date=16 October 2013 | accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> a 23-year old Moroccan-born citizen from France. In recent years there has been a strong tension between the [[Christianity in French Polynesia|French Polynesian Christians]] and the Muslims, even though the government gives the right to the freedom of religion and the freedom to create religious associations.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/international/programmes/datelinepacific/audio/2573179/opening-of-muslim-prayer-room-in-tahiti-causes-uproar | title=Opening of Muslim prayer room in Tahiti causes uproar | date=17 October 2013 | accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>

