{{Infobox mountain | name = Yoshino Mountain | native_name = 吉野山 | native_name_lang = ja | photo = Cherry blossoms at Yoshinoyama 02.jpg | photo_caption = Cherry blossoms at Mount Yoshino | elevation = | prominence = | listing = | language = [[Japanese language|Japanese]] | location = [[Yoshino, Nara|Yoshino-cho]], [[Yoshino District, Nara|Yoshino-gun]], [[Nara Prefecture|Nara]], [[Japan]] | range = | coordinates = | topo = | type = spikey mountain | age = | last_eruption = | first_ascent = 420 BC | easiest_route = | embedded = {{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site | child = yes | official_name = Yoshino and Ômine - Yoshinoyama | part_of = [[Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range]] | criteria = {{UNESCO WHS type|(ii), (iii), (iv), (vi)}}(ii), (iii), (iv), (vi) | ID = 1142bis-001 | coordinates = {{coord|34|21|24|N|135|52|14|E|region:JP-19|display=title, inline|format=dms}} | year = 2004 | extension = 2016 | area = {{convert|33.7|ha|acre|abbr=on}} | buffer_zone = {{convert|916|ha|acre|abbr=on}} | locmapin = Japan | map_caption = }} }}
{{nihongo|'''Yoshino Mountain'''|吉野山|Yoshino-yama}} is a mountain located in the town of [[Yoshino, Nara|Yoshino]] in [[Yoshino District, Nara|Yoshino District]], [[Nara Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. In 2004, it was designated as part of a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] under the name ''[[Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range]]''.
Yoshino Mountain was the subject of a ''[[Waka (poetry)|waka]]'' poem in the 10th century poetry compilation ''[[Kokin Wakashū]]''. It is also the subject of several poems in the ''[[Ogura Hyakunin Isshu]]''.<ref>Mostow, Joshua S., ed. (1996). ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image'', p. 56.</ref>
Several important religious and pilgrimage destinations are located around Mount Yoshino, including [[Yoshino Mikumari Shrine]], [[Kinpu Shrine (Yoshino)|Kimpu Shrine]], and [[Kimpusen-ji]]. It is well known for its [[Sakura|cherry blossom]]s, and attracts many visitors every autumn.
Yoshino Mountain is famous for its many thousands of [[sakura]] trees, and is heavily referenced in both traditional ''[[Waka (poetry)|waka]]'' poetry and folk song for its abundance of flowers in the spring, with famous poets such as [[Fukuda Chiyo-ni|Chiyo]] offering prose on the peak and its many flowers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gill |first1=Robin |title=Cherry Blossom Epiphany: The Poetry and Philosophy of a Flowering Tree |date=2006 |publisher=Paraverse Press |isbn=0974261866 |pages=632–678 of 740 |edition=1st }}</ref> These flowering specimen trees were planted in four groves at different altitudes, in part so that the famed trees would come into bloom at different times of the spring. A 1714 account explained that, on their climb to the top, travelers would be able to enjoy the lower 1,000 cherry trees at the base, the middle 1,000 on the way, the upper 1,000 toward the top, and the 1,000 in the precincts of the inner shrine at the top.<ref>Kaibara Ekiken. (1714). [http://jpimg.digital.archives.go.jp/kouseisai/category/emaki/yoshinoyama_e.html ''Yoshinoyama syokeizu''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305055950/http://jpimg.digital.archives.go.jp/kouseisai/category/emaki/yoshinoyama_e.html |date=March 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref>Stokes, Henry Scott. [https://www.nytimes.com/1983/03/06/travel/cherry-blossom-time-puts-japan-at-ease.html?&pagewanted=2 "Cherry Blossom Time Puts Japan at Ease"], ''[[The New York Times]]''. March 6, 1983.</ref>
Famous products that can be found in shops in the area of Mount Yoshino include edible goods made from [[Kudzu|''kudzu'']] root and persimmon leaf-wrapped [[sushi]] (''kakinoha-zushi).''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=jSQzR6_h9yEC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=Yoshino+Kudzu&source=bl&ots=PYHyRkm3Ov&sig=l64eUecicYinEC8lNFFAkISn8eM&hl=ja&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjr5vmzhN_bAhUZA4gKHSBMDYkQ6AEITDAI#v=onepage&q=Yoshino%20Kudzu&f=false|title=The Book of Kudzu: A Culinary & Healing Guide|last=Shurtleff|first=William|last2=Aoyagi|first2=Akiko|date=1977|publisher=Soyinfo Center|isbn=9780394420684|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yoshinoyama-sakura.jp/english/souvenir.htm|title=Mt. Yoshino Tourist Association｜souvenir|website=www.yoshinoyama-sakura.jp|access-date=2018-06-19}}</ref>
