In [[Greco-Roman]] [[mythology]], '''Sergestus''' was a [[Troy|Trojan]] friend of [[Aeneas]].  He was the ancestor of [[gens Sergia]], a famous [[Patrician (post-Roman Europe)|Patrician]] family of which [[Catilina]] was a member.

In Virgil's ''[[Aeneid]]'', during a [[funeral games (antiquity)|funerary ship race]] Aeneas gives to Sergestus a [[Crete|Cretan]] slave girl named Pholoe in gratitude for saving both ship and crew.<ref>Source: [[Virgil]], [[Aeneid]], v. 288</ref>

{{Quote|And Serguestus, from the house of the name Sergia|Virgil, Sergestusque, domus tenet a quo Sergia nomen, Aeneid (Latin)}}

Sergestus also appears as a minor character in Christopher Marlowe's play ''[[Dido, Queen of Carthage (play)|Dido, Queen of Carthage]]''.

